  <entry>
    <id>https://doi.org/10.1287/isre.2023.0233</id>
    <title>Securing Personal Space in the Crowd: Physical Crowdedness and Organic Mobile Usage</title>
    <updated>2026-06-25T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Xiaoni Lu, Hyeokkoo Eric Kwon, Siliang (Jack) Tong, Xi Zhao, Hsing Kenneth Cheng</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt;Information Systems Research&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;Public transit is a major setting in which individuals spend time on smartphones. This study shows that physical crowdedness is positively associated with organic smartphone usage, with stronger relationships for social functionalities, among users with shorter prior trips, during off-peak periods, and when individuals are surrounded by different-age groups. These findings offer actionable guidance for app developers, mobile advertisers, and telecom providers. Users in crowded environments appear to actively seek functionalities that help them reclaim a sense of personal space, suggesting that mobile strategies can be made more adaptive, personalized, and context-aware. For app categories that perform poorly under crowded conditions, such as shopping apps, platforms may benefit from embedding features that strengthen self-esteem and perceived control, for example, socially informed recommendations or try-before-you-buy options. More broadly, because high levels of organic mobile usage often precede effective promotional engagement, firms can better identify high-impact windows for targeted advertising strategies, such as socially engaged users in crowded transit contexts during off-peak hours.</content>
    <link href="https://doi.org/10.1287/isre.2023.0233"/>
    <category term="Information Systems Research"/>
    <published>2026-06-25T00:00:00+00:00</published>
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <id>https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhag059</id>
    <title>Mutual Fund Flows at Long Horizons</title>
    <updated>2026-06-26T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Hendrik Bessembinder, Shuaiyu Chen, Michael J Cooper, Jinming Xue, Feng Zhang</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt;The Review of Financial Studies&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;We show that positive flows to active mutual funds with high recent returns partially reverse at longer horizons. This outcome is robust across a broad range of alternative specifications. Reversal occurs from greater outflows associated with high prior returns, not reduced inflows. We test theories to explain the reversal: investment life cycles, tax loss selling, and a behavioral “disappointment” hypothesis based on investors’ overreaction to positive returns. While both tax loss selling and short investor life cycles can contribute, the evidence supports a role for investor disappointment, whereby investors redeem their capital when return performance fails to meet expectations. (JEL G10, G23)</content>
