    <title>Partnerships for Social Cohesion and Social Impact: How Corporate‐Community Co‐Development Constitutes an Impactful
                    &lt;scp&gt;HR&lt;/scp&gt;
                    Initiative</title>
    <updated>2026-07-02T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Cristina B. Gibson, Jennifer Gibbs, Nitzan Navick, Kimberly McGinnis</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt;Human Resource Management&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;Organizational scholars have begun to recognize the importance of social cohesion, but we know little about how it can lead to broader social impact, and even less about the role of human resource management (HRM) in these processes. To investigate this link, we examined corporate community co‐development as a particularly impactful HRM initiative. The program involved a Silicon Valley technology company partnering with five nonprofit organizations. Our study comprised a comprehensive mixed‐method longitudinal design involving 62 interviews and 382 h of field observations combined with a large‐scale quantitative survey (n= 1101). The findings reveal that HR managers not only facilitated the logistics of the program but also helped to create three generative tensions: the balancing of belonging and uniqueness, of the familiar and the unfamiliar, and of within‐sector and across‐sector connections. HRM helped participants navigate these tensions through specific processes that combined human and social capital to develop social cohesion. We also empirically demonstrate that social cohesion was positively associated with social impact in both the company and the nonprofits.</content>
